## Discord Channel

{{INSTANCE_NAME}} can receive tasks via Discord. Wire via `claude /discord:configure` after installing the `discord@claude-plugins-official` plugin.

- Messages in Discord = task queue items. Do the work, report results.
- Same hard limits apply: no publishing, no sending emails, no merging PRs without {{INSTALLER_NAME}}'s approval.
- Channel context matters. Document your channel topology + per-channel defaults below:

| Channel | Purpose | Default behavior |
|---|---|---|
| `#{{PRIMARY_CHANNEL}}` | Conversation, task intake | Treat as full task queue |
| `#{{OPS_CHANNEL}}` | System alerts, heartbeat failures | Read-only signal |
| `#{{BRIEFINGS_CHANNEL}}` | Daily briefing delivery | Outbound only via `post-to-channel.sh briefings` |

(Per-installer extensions: add channels for plugins as you enable them, e.g. `#{{HEALTH_CHANNEL}}` for BFL, `#{{SOCIAL_CHANNEL}}` for dating.)

## Voice Notes

When a Discord message has an audio attachment (content type `audio/`), it's a voice note:

1. Download the attachment via `download_attachment`
2. Transcribe via `bash ${CHASSIS_HOME}/chassis/scripts/transcribe-voice.sh <file>`
3. Treat the transcription as the user's typed message — execute the task, don't echo back
4. React with 🎧 to acknowledge receipt
5. **Voice reply only when explicitly asked** ("read it back", "voice reply", "audio"). Default reply is text. When generating, use `bash ${CHASSIS_HOME}/chassis/scripts/text-to-speech.sh "<text>"` and attach the MP3 alongside the text reply

## Loom Videos

When a Discord message contains a Loom URL:

1. React with 🎬 to acknowledge
2. Run `bash ${CHASSIS_HOME}/chassis/scripts/process-loom.sh <loom-url>`
3. Read transcript + key frames to understand the demo
4. Execute the task being shown, don't echo back

## Discord Triggers

The chassis supports the trigger-keyword pattern: an inbound Discord message starting with a known keyword dispatches to a handler. Each trigger is documented per-plugin (see `plugins/<name>/CLAUDE.md`).

Pattern (the chassis enforces; each trigger fills in the body):

1. Detect keyword case-insensitively at message start in a target channel
2. Parse message body per the trigger's grammar
3. React with an emoji to acknowledge
4. Hand off to the handler script / plugin

The chassis ships ZERO triggers by default. Add your own under this section in your installer-specific CLAUDE.md (this file). Examples from V1:
- `Pacman <url>` — URL self-improvement filter (Sean's V1 reference; lives in his V1 install only)
- `Backfill: <description>` — manual meal entry (BFL plugin; activates when bfl module enabled)

## Scheduled Tasks — Heartbeat Dispatcher

{{INSTANCE_NAME}} uses the chassis heartbeat dispatcher (see `docs/heartbeat-dispatcher.md`). A single launchd / systemd unit runs every 15 minutes, parses `${CHASSIS_HOME}/HEARTBEATS.md`, and only invokes `claude -p` when there's actual work.

| launchd / systemd label | Purpose | Schedule |
|---|---|---|
| `com.behalfbot.heartbeat-dispatcher` | Runs the dispatcher | Every 15 min |

See `${CHASSIS_HOME}/HEARTBEATS.md` (installer-rendered from `chassis/HEARTBEATS.md.template`) for the registry; per-heartbeat schemas live in that file.

